consent:
CPHS# 2013-08-5546 

 

Dear Participant,



 

This study is being conducted by Mahesh Srinivasan, assistant professor of psychology at the University of California, Berkeley, and his laboratory of research assistants, graduate students, and post-doctoral fellows. We invite you to participate in a study exploring language and cognition in adulthood. Please read the following information carefully and sign this form if you wish to participate. Participation is entirely voluntary. If anything is not clear, please do not hesitate to ask questions.

 

Study Procedures

There will be 1 session, lasting no longer than 30-45 minutes. During this session, you will participate in experiments about language and cognition. We investigate a variety of topics including people’s knowledge of words and grammatical structures, and how this relates to their understanding of concepts (e.g., their knowledge of objects, substances, time, and number), and their ability to understand the intentions and goals of others (e.g., what other people believe and want). Additionally, we explore how these abilities are shaped by the environment in which people are raised, and thus explore how learning different languages affect how people think, and how culture influences people’s basic cognition (e.g., their moral reasoning, beliefs about themselves and others, and ability to learn from and share with others). Our research takes the form of short, interactive studies that are designed to be engaging.

 

You will participate in one or a combination of the following tasks: 

·         Language comprehension and production tasks (e.g., figuring out what language means and how it should be used)

·         General cognitive tasks (e.g., remembering things, controlling impulses)

·         Categorization/association tasks (e.g., sorting objects or stating what comes to mind given a prompt)

·         Search tasks (e.g., searching for or hiding objects, using maps/pictures)

·         Temporal reasoning tasks (e.g., estimating duration, placing events on a timeline)

·         Quantity tasks (e.g., estimating number of items, counting, deciding which set has more)

·         Morality/sharing tasks (e.g., making moral judgments, sharing resources with others)

·         Beliefs/attitudes tasks (e.g., expressing beliefs/attitudes about the world, yourself, and others)

·         Social group tasks (e.g., reasoning about individuals from different social groups)

·         Imitation tasks (e.g., imitating a presented action)

 

These studies may present you with a variety of objects, images, or videos, and ask you to answer questions or make judgments. In some studies, you will be asked to view images or watch videos on a computer screen. 

 

Benefits

You will not receive any direct benefits. However, you will be making a substantial contribution to improving our understanding of language and thought, and by placing children’s linguistic and cognitive development in context.

 

Risks/Discomforts

We do not expect you to face any foreseeable risks from your participation. However, there is the unlikely possibility that your confidentiality will be compromised but we have taken measures to minimize this risk. Usually, people enjoy participating in these studies, but if you would like to stop at any point, you can. 

 

Confidentiality

Your identity will be separated from your data and a numerical code will be assigned to keep track of the data transcriptions. Your confidentiality will be kept to the degree permitted by the technology being used. No guarantees can be made regarding the interception of data sent via the Internet by any third parties. Data will be kept indefinitely in case further analysis is required. All information collected during the research will be securely stored at the University in locked file cabinets and password-protected computers housed in secure rooms. Only laboratory personnel will have access to this data. No individuals will be identified in any presentation or publication.

 

Costs of Study Participation

There are no costs associated with study participation.

 

Compensation
For your participation in our research, you may receive: course credit, cash, a gift card, or a small gift. You may refuse to complete any part(s) of the study that make you feel uncomfortable and still receive full compensation. Research Participation Program (RPP): If you are participating through RPP, you will receive a ½ course credit if the study is less than one hour and 1.5 credits for studies that take 2 hours. Amazon’s Mturk/Prolific: If you are participating through Amazon’s Mturk or Prolific, you will receive between $1.33 and $16 per task, depending on the time it takes to complete the type of task you’ve been assigned. If the task takes 10 minutes or less to complete, you will receive $1.33.  If the task takes between 10 and 20 minutes to complete, you will receive $2.50.  If the task takes between 20 and 30 minutes to complete, you will receive $4.00, and so on up to a maximum of $16.00 for a task that takes 110-120 minutes. Payments may also be adjusted depending on how difficult or enjoyable the task is, or how difficult it is to recruit participants (e.g., if we are looking for subjects who speak a specific language, in addition to English). Your online account will be credited directly. Prolific: If you are participating through Prolific, you will receive between $1.60 and $19.20 per task, depending on the time it takes to complete the type of task you’ve been assigned. If the task takes 10 minutes or less to complete, you will receive $1.60.  If the task takes between 10 and 20 minutes to complete, you will receive $3.20.  If the task takes between 20 and 30 minutes to complete, you will receive $4.80, and so on up to a maximum of $19.20 for a task that takes 110-120 minutes. Payments may also be adjusted to add a bonus depending on how difficult or enjoyable the task is, your performance, or how difficult it is to recruit participants (e.g., if we are looking for subjects who speak a specific language, in addition to English). Your online account will be credited directly. Social Science Laboratory (Xlab): If you are participating through Xlab, you will receive cash or a gift card (per Xlab guidelines, on average $15/hr rate). All other participants: You receive a small thank you gift, or you will receive cash or a gift card ($10/hr rate).
NOTE: Our online studies contain a number of checks to make sure that participants are finishing the tasks honestly and completely. As long as you read the instructions and complete the tasks, your survey response (for Amazon’s Mturk, known as “HIT”) will be approved. If you fail these checks, your survey response (for Amazon’s Mturk, known as “HIT”) will be rejected and you will not be paid.
 
Alternatives to Participation

If you are participating through RPP, alternatives to participating in this research study are available to you. You may choose to participate in another RPP study or request a non-RPP alternative research assignment from your course instructor. Alternative assignments are estimated to be equivalent in terms of time and effort to participating in this study.

 

Rights

Please understand that your participation in the research is voluntary and that you are free to withdraw and discontinue participation in the research at any time. If you decide not to participate, there will be no penalty or loss of benefits to which you are otherwise entitled. Whether or not you participate in this study will have no bearing on your status with respect to any program, department, or service at the University of California, and will involve no adverse consequences to your school enrollment or coursework.

 

Questions

If you have any questions at this point, you can contact the lab at 510-664-4494, Professor Mahesh Srinivasan at 650-823-9488, or email us at one of the addresses listed below, if you have any questions or concerns later.

 

If you have any questions regarding your treatment or rights as a participant in this research project, please contact the Committee for the Protection of Human Subjects at the University of California at Berkeley at phone: (510) 642-7461, or at subjects@berkeley.edu.

 

Thank you for your time. 

 

Sincerely,

Dr. Mahesh Srinivasan, Assistant Professor of  Psychology, University of California, Berkeley

 

Additional Contact Information: 

Mahesh Srinivasan, Principal Investigator: srinivasan@berkeley.edu

Lab Coordinator: lcdlab@berkeley.edu
 

Consent

 

If you agree to participate in this study, please select the consent option below.

 

By selecting the “I consent” button below, I acknowledge that I am 18 or older and have read this consent form, and I agree to take part in the research.

gen_feedback:
Two of the definitions were especially triggering to me, which is what led to the extreme difficulty, as I was trying to complete this survey whilst having a panic attack. I'm still shaking terribly, so please forgive any typos, though I am trying my level best to leave none. 

The two statements in particular were for the words "catch" and "stone." There is nothing wrong with these words in and of themselves, but the examples were needlessly violent, and specifically triggered flashbacks to a concussion I suffered around age 11. There was no warning that there could be potentially triggering content, and I was caught entirely unprepared.

The examples were, "The rock caught her in the back of the head" and "He threw a stone at me."

For more detail, my specific incident was related to two boys from my grade, throwing rocks at the back of my head while on the way home from school, because they thought I was a witch. I will not go into more detail, but I hope you can understand why this btrought up some bad thoughts for me, and whu it might make my results a little unreliable after those questions.
